### 5. Which searching algorithm is more efficient? Why?

**Answer:** The experiment only used Linear Search (O(n)). Binary Search (O(log n)) would be more efficient.

**Linear Search Analysis:**
- Time increases linearly with array size
- n=10: 3,000 ns
- n=100: 1,300 ns (unexpected drop - possible JVM warmup)
- n=1000: 11,600 ns

**Why Binary Search would be better:**
- **Linear Search:** O(n) - checks each element sequentially
- **Binary Search:** O(log n) - divides search space in half each time
- For n=1,000,000:
  - Linear: up to 1,000,000 comparisons
  - Binary: only ~20 comparisons

**Binary Search Efficiency:**
- 1000 elements → ~10 comparisons maximum
- 1,000,000 elements → ~20 comparisons maximum
- Exponentially faster for large datasets

### 6. Why does Binary Search require a sorted array?
**Answer:** Binary Search relies on the **ordered property** of the array to make decisions.
**Explanation:**
1. **Divide and Conquer Logic:**
   - Binary Search compares the target with the middle element
   - If target < middle → search LEFT half
   - If target > middle → search RIGHT half
   - If equal → found

2. **Requirement for Order:**
   - The algorithm assumes all elements in left half are LESS than middle
   - All elements in right half are GREATER than middle
   - This is only true if the array is SORTED

3. **What happens with unsorted array:**
Unsorted: [5, 2, 8, 1, 9]
Search for 1, middle element = 8
Since array is unsorted:
Elements left of 8: [5, 2] → contains 1 but we would skip it!
Binary Search would incorrectly go to left/right half
Would miss elements that are in the "wrong" half



# Algorithm Performance Analysis: Sorting and Searching

## A. Project Overview

### Description of Selected Algorithms

This project implements and compares three fundamental algorithms:

| Category | Algorithm | Time Complexity | Space Complexity |
|----------|-----------|----------------|------------------|
| **Basic Sorting** | Selection Sort | O(n²) | O(1) |
| **Advanced Sorting** | Quick Sort | O(n log n) average, O(n²) worst | O(log n) |
| **Searching** | Linear Search | O(n) | O(1) |

### Purpose of the Experiment

The experiment aims to:
1. Compare the actual performance of basic vs advanced sorting algorithms
2. Analyze how input size and data distribution affect algorithm efficiency
3. Verify theoretical time complexity with empirical measurements
4. Understand when to choose different algorithms for real-world applications

## B. Algorithm Descriptions

### 1. Selection Sort (Basic Sorting)

**How it works:**
- Divides array into sorted and unsorted regions
- Repeatedly finds the minimum element from unsorted region
- Swaps it with the first element of unsorted region
- Expands sorted region by one element each iteration

**Step-by-step example:**
Initial: [64, 25, 12, 22, 11]
Step 1: Find min(11) → swap with index 0 → [11, 25, 12, 22, 64]
Step 2: Find min(12) → swap with index 1 → [11, 12, 25, 22, 64]
Step 3: Find min(22) → swap with index 2 → [11, 12, 22, 25, 64]
Step 4: Find min(25) → swap with index 3 → [11, 12, 22, 25, 64]

**Time Complexity:**
- Best Case: O(n²) - always scans entire unsorted portion
- Average Case: O(n²) - same number of comparisons regardless of input
- Worst Case: O(n²) - no early termination possible

**Space Complexity:** O(1) - sorts in-place
### 2. Quick Sort (Advanced Sorting)

**How it works:**
- Uses divide-and-conquer strategy
- Selects a pivot element (middle element in our implementation)
- Partitions array so elements < pivot go left, > pivot go right
- Recursively sorts left and right subarrays

**Step-by-step example:**
Initial: [64, 25, 12, 22, 11]
Step 1: Choose pivot = 12 (middle)
Step 2: Partition → [11, 12, 25, 22, 64]
Step 3: Recursively sort left [11] and right [25, 22, 64]
Step 4: Right partition with pivot 22 → [22, 25, 64]
Step 5: Final → [11, 12, 22, 25, 64]

**Time Complexity:**
- Best Case: O(n log n) - perfectly balanced partitions
- Average Case: O(n log n) - random data creates balanced partitions
- Worst Case: O(n²) - already sorted with bad pivot selection (not an issue with our middle-pivot implementation)

**Space Complexity:** O(log n) - recursive call stack

### 3. Linear Search (Searching)

**How it works:**
- Sequentially checks each element in the array
- Compares each element with target value
- Returns index when found, -1 if not found

**Step-by-step example:**
Array: [64, 25, 12, 22, 11]
Search for: 22

Step 1: Check index 0 → 64 ≠ 22
Step 2: Check index 1 → 25 ≠ 22
Step 3: Check index 2 → 12 ≠ 22
Step 4: Check index 3 → 22 = 22 → Return 3

**Time Complexity:**
- Best Case: O(1) - element at first position
- Average Case: O(n) - check half the elements on average
- Worst Case: O(n) - element at last position or not present

**Space Complexity:** O(1) - no extra space needed
